initial_story:
The baby suffered a cardiac arrest at the theme park on Thursday

A woman has been arrested on suspicion of neglecting a five-month-old boy who suffered a cardiac arrest at a theme park.

The baby is in a critical condition in hospital following the incident at Legoland Windsor at about 13:00 BST on Thursday, police said.

A 27-year-old woman from Witham, Essex, was arrested on suspicion of neglecting a child to cause unnecessary injury.

She has been released on bail until 26 July.

Det Con Zoe Eele, of Thames Valley Police's Child Abuse Investigation Unit, said: "Firstly, our thoughts are with the family of the boy who is in a critical condition in hospital after suffering a cardiac arrest.

"We are working closely with the team at Legoland Windsor Resort but would like to speak to anyone who have information about this incident, specifically anyone who was queueing for the Coastguard HQ boat ride between around 11.30am and 12:45pm.

"I would ask for the public to please avoid speculation about the incident and to respect the boy's family at this deeply upsetting time."

Police said they are not looking for further suspects in relation to the incident.

In a statement, the theme park said: "On Thursday, a young guest was taken ill... and our fully trained First Aid team administered immediate care until the emergency services arrived.

"We will continue to support Thames Valley Police with their ongoing investigation."

A catastrophic accident involving a ride at an amusement park in Japan has left a 35-year-old man fighting for his life in intensive care. 

The incident occurred on Saturday at the Fuji-Q Highland theme park in Yamanashi Prefecture, where a rollercoaster derailed and crashed into the queue area, injuring multiple people.

According to eyewitnesses, the ride, known as the Dodonpa, was moving at high speed when it suddenly lurched to one side, sending debris flying in all directions. Passengers were thrown from their seats, with some falling several feet to the ground.

Japanese authorities have launched an investigation into the accident, with police questioning the ride's operators and reviewing surveillance footage to determine the cause of the derailment.

"I was screaming for my life," said one of the survivors, still shaken by the traumatic experience. "I thought for sure I was going to die."

The theme park, one of Japan's most popular attractions, has suspended operations of the rollercoaster pending further investigation.

A catastrophic fire broke out on a luxury cruise ship in the Mediterranean, leaving dozens of passengers scrambling to evacuate the burning vessel. The blaze started in the ship's engine room, sending flames shooting out of the deck and black smoke billowing into the sky.

A massive quake struck the coastal city, reducing downtown skyscrapers to rubble. The tremor sent shockwaves through the bustling streets, causing widespread destruction and panic. Amidst the chaos, survivors scrambled to escape the crumbling buildings, dodging falling debris and shards of glass as they sought refuge from the inferno of destruction.
